paragraphs.text:
%md

# Retail Data Analysis

This notebook is used to do analysis on the retail data that is sourced from a MySQL database.

Following steps are done as part of this notebook:
    * Moving the data from a MySQL database to **Apache Hive** using **Apache Sqoop**'s import-all-tables command
    * Using **Apache Zeppelin** dynamic forms to describe the **Apache Hive** retail_db schema and also view sample data for a said sample size
    * Using **Apache Hive** to do a detailed analysis of the Retail data available
    
Thank you!!

msg.data:
Retail Data Analysis

This notebook is used to do analysis on the retail data that is sourced from a MySQL database.

Following steps are done as part of this notebook:
* Moving the data from a MySQL database to Apache Hive using Apache Sqoop’s import-all-tables command
* Using Apache Zeppelin dynamic forms to describe the Apache Hive retail_db schema and also view sample data for a said sample size
* Using Apache Hive to do a detailed analysis of the Retail data available

Thank you!!

    p.product_name,
    round(sum(oi.order_item_subtotal),2) as revenue

    retail_db.order_items oi
    inner join retail_db.products p on (oi.order_item_product_id = p.product_id)

paragraphs.text:
%md

## Customer Analysis

The below query gives an overview of a customer.

The following questions can be answered using the below query:
    * Since when is he/she a customer
    * When was the last order placed and the days since the last order
    * Number of orders placed. Out of them how many were processed or not
    * Number of products the customer has purchased from the product catalog
    * Revenue generated by the customer

msg.data:
Customer Analysis

The below query gives an overview of a customer.

The following questions can be answered using the below query:
* Since when is he/she a customer
* When was the last order placed and the days since the last order
* Number of orders placed. Out of them how many were processed or not
* Number of products the customer has purchased from the product catalog
* Revenue generated by the customer

paragraphs.text:
%hive

select 
    co.name name,
    co.city city,
    co.state state,
    co.zipcode zip,
    co.customer_since customer_since,
    max(co.order_date) last_ordered, --when was the last order placed by the customer
    datediff(current_date(),max(co.order_date)) days_since_last_order, --days since the last order was placed by the customer
    int(coalesce(round(avg(days_from_previous_order)),0)) days_between_orders, --average days between orders placed by the customer
    count(distinct co.order_id) orders_placed, --total number of orders placed by the customer
    count(distinct case when co.order_status not in ('CANCELED', 'SUSPECTED_FRAUD') then co.order_id end) processed_orders, --out of the total, the number of orders that were processed
    count(distinct case when co.order_status in ('CANCELED', 'SUSPECTED_FRAUD') then co.order_id end) non_processed_orders, --the number of orders that were not processed due to cancellation or suspected fraud
    count(distinct case when co.order_status not in ('CANCELED', 'SUSPECTED_FRAUD') then oi.order_item_product_id end) products_purchased, --number of products purchased from the catalog
    round(sum(case when co.order_status not in ('CANCELED', 'SUSPECTED_FRAUD') then oi.order_item_subtotal else 0 end),2) revenue --revenue generated by the customer for processed orders only
from 
    retail_db.order_items oi 
    inner join 
        (select 
            concat_ws(', ', c.customer_lname, c.customer_fname) as name,
            c.customer_city as city,
            c.customer_state as state,
            c.customer_zipcode as zipcode,
            from_unixtime(int(o.order_date/1000)) as order_date,
            from_unixtime(int(lag(o.order_date) over (partition by o.order_customer_id order by o.order_date)/1000)) as previous_order_date, -- get the previous date the customer placed an order
            datediff(from_unixtime(int(o.order_date/1000)), from_unixtime(int(lag(o.order_date) over (partition by o.order_customer_id order by o.order_date)/1000))) as days_from_previous_order, -- get the number of days between an order
            from_unixtime(int(first_value(o.order_date) over (partition by o.order_customer_id order by o.order_date)/1000)) as customer_since, -- get the date from when he/she is a customer
            o.order_id as order_id,
            o.order_status as order_status,
            c.customer_id as customer_id
        from
            retail_db.customers c
            inner join retail_db.orders o on (c.customer_id = o.order_customer_id)) co on (oi.order_item_order_id = co.order_id)
group by
    co.name,
    co.city,
    co.state,
    co.zipcode,
    co.customer_since;
